Inventing – it’s serious business here at REA

Article by Kimi George
Published on 22nd Feb 2018 — Read in 2 mins

Share

  • Tweet about it
  • Share this on LinkedIn
  • Share this on Facebook

At REA Group, we’ve changed our focus from innovation to invention, and we encourage our people to take the ‘no idea is too small’ approach to their work.

This is mostly evident in our REA Inventorship days (more efficiently known as REAio internally), a cultural event that happens four times a year across our business in Australia and now is rolling out to our Asian businesses.

The premise of the event is simple: for three days once a quarter, every REA Group employee has the opportunity to step away from their regular day job and work on any project they choose or feel passionately about. Sounds great, right? The only catch is that at the end of the three days, you must share what you’ve learnt with your peers.

Hackathon events aren’t a new phenomenon, but the main point of difference between our Inventorship days compared to other events is that we focus on learning, rather than shipping. Like our company belief, our Inventorship days aren’t about innovation but instead are intended to facilitate the lost art of invention.

So what do we mean by invention? Think of it as the process of putting two ideas together to create a new third idea, for example a phone + an empty room in your house = crowd sourced short term leasing.  Similarly, think of innovation as the process of putting that third idea into your customer’s hands (shipping something), for example a functional mobile phone app + user research + marketing = AirBnB.

We held our first Inventorship Day in March 2010 after being inspired by companies like Atlassian (ShipIt Days) & Google (20% time). In the early days, our events were led by a small but passionate group of employees: 13 developers working on a handful of ideas, with a heavily technical skew and a strong focus on shipping something _useful_. But with each subsequent event, we’ve set out to implement the complementary philosophies of kaizen (continuous improvement) and kaikaku (radical change) to build these days into something bigger and better each quarter.

As a result, the scale of the Inventorship Days we hold today are a far cry from the original however, at its heart, the core principles remain true.  And you can see a taste of what they look like yourself in the video of our last Inventorship Day.

In brief, some of the value we gain from continuing to invest in this event includes:

– Allowing our people the space to learn something new

– Encouraging people to work with someone new, or take up a new role within a team

– Setting aside the day-to-day grind and shifting into a more creative way of thinking

We consistently prioritise these three values as being the pillars of Inventorship Days, and if we make sure we get these right, then everything else will take care of itself.  By maintaining this sense of continuity, we’re constantly discovering the exponential reach of these benefits throughout the business as more time passes.
